{"title":"What I’ve been reading","link":"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/901254872/0/marginalrevolution~What-Ive-been-reading.html","date":1721018648000,"content":"<p>1. Kimmo Rentola, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/How-Finland-Survived-Stalin-1939-1950/dp/0300273614/ref=tmm_hrd_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.L96bUJWrptfO7B9JanLc_8a7VgJvBHqYzuySTMbhjF7GjHj071QN20LucGBJIEps.pfAQLYra45ydd3EriY0EgfiOhUC_-q97BCygS3If6Ic&amp;qid=1720978666&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">How Finland Survived Stalin: From Winter War to Cold War</a>.  An excellent book, especially good on linking the Winter War with the fighting of 1944 and also the postwar settlments.  Winner of the Lauri Jäntti prize, who would have thought otherwise?</p>\r\n<p>2. Sjeng Scheijen, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Avant-Gardists-Artists-Revolt-Russian-1917-1935/dp/0500024553/ref=sr_1_1?crid=B0FK47EZ03XC&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.6SFeF1v9dMydjjspFzmgkg.SxTnEUZPchk4-IURsbnJBKGHJItLjKILHClwLckH_Co&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Sjeng+Scheijen%2C+Avant-Gardists%3A+Artists+in+Revolt+in+the+Russian+Empire+and+the+Soviet+Union+1917-1935&amp;qid=1720978739&amp;sprefix=sjeng+scheijen%2C+avant-gardists+artists+in+revolt+in+the+russian+empire+and+the+soviet+union+1917-1935%2Caps%2C59&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Avant-Gardists: Artists in Revolt in the Russian Empire and the Soviet Union 1917-1935</a>.  My biggest learning from this volume was simply how important Vladimir Tatlin was as a leader of the Soviet avant-garde in the 1920s.  He might have mattered as much as Malevich?  It is worth buying and reading a book for an insight such as that.  Here is <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dlWdEJiv0TI\" target=\"_blank\">a short video</a> of a good Tatlin exhibit from Basel, twelve years ago.  The book also offered this sentence: “The affinity between the anarchists and the futurists is not so surprising.”</p>\r\n<p>As a follow-up, I’ve also been reading Norbert Lynton, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Tatlins-Tower-Revolution-Norbert-Lynton/dp/0300111304/ref=sr_1_7?crid=UKEO9QJ843CC&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.Twgum8wjW3a-Trl7eheYKGADkgVT972b6R0Sxb9YBdw94Kk_wj6oYP8I-txHVDK3_rP6NOe7FO3sH7N9zR6-SHYBmcP3N1EYKTamLiGy9uEP6Fk9sMoUJB04zqS_LKb8N4HQTpWIDgqHnKrUjBrulFYlFbW3VMefHM4deQxN94KVKkq1EDwNoDrz6e7xgQe-9_e_bozcKi8sFR6GPOT5sCOi9HcvBv1ltJgE7dUaW3c.iMSyIHqqiMKmPGbkwOKuRh8t0dj2dY8hlPsO4WPbI5M&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Norbert+Lynton&amp;qid=1720978823&amp;sprefix=norbert+lynton%2Caps%2C56&amp;sr=8-7\" target=\"_blank\">Tatlin’s Tower: Monument to Revolution</a>, also very good.</p>\r\n<p>3. Harriet Baker, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Rural-Hours-Harriet-Baker/dp/0241540518/ref=sr_1_1?crid=1FW7ROYG4BB7A&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.0lhaAtRsyXt4W7MIr3uBJNh-6YXAhMr6Mx85BPyzEs3GjHj071QN20LucGBJIEps.4zFjoaxyxSKuMGnTPbDC1r6PIgeSBb3T_P9tMZ1UWS0&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=harriet+baker+rural+hours&amp;qid=1720978455&amp;sprefix=harriet+baker%2Caps%2C87&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Rural Hours: The Country Lives of Virginia Woolf, Sylvia Townsend Warner, and Rosamond Lehmann</a>.  What is it like to be an unusual woman writer, with unusual proclivities, and have to build up or rebuild your work life in the countryside?  There is now a whole book on this topic.  Does it really mean you have to write down a complete inventory of all household possessions? (apparently)  Beautifully written, very British, will frustrate those who seek generalization but recommended nonetheless.</p>\r\n<p>4. <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Carlo-Scarpa-Buildings-Emiliano-Bugatti/dp/3791377140/ref=sr_1_1?crid=2QV6SN40IZ2PL&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.JKWXs0NDmW2vMRA8unahTQvdZA7JloGsAtTzbMT-6xf23QidWVGy7SJktvOhqMLYHtDcqoYb1g2O8cp88HrZadCtoB6oD_Bg6K-GRhzBWrI.d6SqC0DCQKd8_CTt6KQJGimU0gJTphB9zm76ssGKiC4&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=carlo+scarpa+the+complete+buildings&amp;qid=1720978362&amp;sprefix=carlo+scarpa%2Caps%2C90&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Carlo Scarpa: The Complete Buildings</a>, edited by Emiliano Bugatti.  Mostly a picture book, this one convinced me I need to visit Treviso, Italy.  The <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.archdaily.com/991218/architecture-that-hides-stories-a-look-at-the-brion-tomb-by-carlo-scarpa\" target=\"_blank\">Brion Tomb</a> is nearby, not to mention the Canova museum, both designed by Scarpa.  He also showed that first-rate architecture never quite ended in Venice proper.  I hadn’t known that Scarpa’s earliest works date as far back as the mid-1930s, and that he died by falling down a flight of stairs.</p>\r\n<p>5. Céline, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/dp/081123732X\" target=\"_blank\">War</a>.  A newly unearthed novel by a great classic author is rare to come by, but here we have one.  The text is not fully intact, but enough is there for reading to be a sufficiently integrated experience.  It is in fact one of the best novels on the horrors of war, and now is not such a bad time to revisit that theme.</p>\r\n<p>I enjoyed Susan Tomes, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Women-Piano-History-50-Lives/dp/030026657X/ref=sr_1_1?crid=M6TJ7M5VZGX3&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.91ByD1jbuClTnsN3ekUwNcD_Gw84k5gSM01TFOv_W17nT8I75HaoZBn_7kDNZutlNFlzNEiNNbqv-H-RyU76k-AP6F8yfJGh-XGjBQPyg7g.3skgUUvwNFCW67nEy33dtcM2bbtWaN1HZnojJnFhGX8&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=women+and+the+piano+susan+tomes&amp;qid=1720978324&amp;sprefix=susan+tomes+wo%2Caps%2C78&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">Women and the Piano: A History in 50 Lives</a>, but it is too skimpy on the moderns.  No coverage of Uchida or Ursula Oppens or Angela Hewitt?</p>\r\n<p>Jack Weatherford, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/Emperor-Seas-Kublai-Making-China/dp/1399417738/ref=sr_1_4?crid=34KQGJ3VVGBTV&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.55RPtsuUtghMzcvY6VOxYMIN6LgnQxkMJ93CQu36wGK4mdJRF0z-NILbqPK5R2Zwwa20KTfoCf8wNrpnhGZWJl0udiRcMcJ_7MPzfmri8PnLcN2Pfz2ABVUpiC9T3J7C-vl2OrnuoXEqnCVWBgB0b16oqqKkzy-EROCPpnGz-zcJT6dtOT-t3T3IXhLXBFXDafqrNYHg_LLQ2P7mFbc3-M9MInZ0RfxkH_1HQdxAjho.XVt9394FLtfjXnug5HWtl06S12ujXK_AxausZQVyqJ8&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=jack+weatherford&amp;qid=1720978244&amp;sprefix=jack+weatherford%2Caps%2C88&amp;sr=8-4\" target=\"_blank\">Emperor of the Seas: Kublai Khan and the Making of China</a> is a good follow-up to his earlier work.</p>\r\n<p>In my pile is Anthony Gregory, <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://www.amazon.com/New-Deal-Law-Order-Liberal-ebook/dp/B0CNM7T6JP/ref=sr_1_1?crid=A7KAYC5QIVD&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.q6_rk8m5a6xY7wa4Z-4KHnurLqH1BEkJl4fnS26s0U9B8jSes0zF0ndyWI7RZYmd6Csh4eEo0dwtssSj95wQYCtZvDPrh2Zz9-hq7UaH5SJSFr6BhPEvDiPc_VKUQFhJwxvlDModJAckY74RPWrm90my_mtf5flokDqortbiROZA8LRZgxRmxXDv7viPQNUL.9Os6ZME4CQZTL96P6mP0YdVHZpoMWTruvPujd-nWhBc&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=anthony+gregory+new+deal&amp;qid=1720978286&amp;sprefix=anthony+gregory+new+deal%2Caps%2C79&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\">New Deal Law and Order: How the War on Crime Built the Modern Liberal State</a>.</p>\r\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2024/07/what-ive-been-reading-256.html\">What I’ve been reading</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/t/0/0/marginalrevolution/~https://marginalrevolution.com\">Marginal REVOLUTION</a>.</p>\r\n<img height=\"1\" width=\"1\" src=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/~/i/901254872/0/marginalrevolution\" />\r\n<div><a href=\"https://feeds.feedblitz.com/_/28/901254872/mar